Decoding Household Debt. Exploring Key Predictors and Model Comparisons Using Machine Learning Techniques.

Michael-Lee, W., Success A., Stephen B., Chris H. Stephen, A.

2025-02-19



Introduction

This research seeks to identify the key demographic and financial predictors of high household debt by leveraging models such as Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA), Quadratic Discriminant Analysis (QDA) decision trees, and Random Forests. The overarching research question is:

“Which demographic and financial factors are the most significant predictors of household debt levels, and how do Linear Discriminant Analysis, Quadratic Discriminant Analysis, and Random Forest models compare in predicting these outcomes?”

This research can benefit various sectors, such as: Banks and Lenders, Government and Policymakers, Debt Counselling Services, etc

The dataset was obtained from the Federal Reserve System of the Central Bank of the United States and is publicly available for use at https://www.federalreserve.gov/econres/scfindex.htm. It is in CSV format and contains financial and demographic information from the 2022 Survey of Consumer Finances (SCF), which surveys over 4,000 U.S. households.

The data includes variables such as: • Financial Information: Debt, investments, pensions, and income. • Demographic Information: Age, sex, marital status, and education level.

The dependent variable will be total household debt, which will be categorised as follows: • 1 (High Debt): Debt levels above a specific threshold (i.e. the median). • 0 (Not High Debt): Debt levels below the defined threshold.

Demographic and financial predictors was selected based on historical research and literature review (see predictors selected in the relevant section in the code below).

# Read the dataset
SCF = read.csv("SCFP2022.csv")

# Create cleaned dataset with selected variables
SCF_clean = SCF %>% 
  dplyr::select(c("DEBT", "INCOME", "ASSET", "CCBAL", "CANTMANG", "LATE", 
                  "FORECLLAST5", "BNKRUPLAST5", "MARRIED", "AGE", "EDUC", 
                  "FINLIT", "BPLANCJ", "HHSEX", "OCCAT2"))

# Extract every 5th row (sampling technique)
row_indices1 <- seq(1, nrow(SCF_clean), by = 5)
data1 <- SCF_clean[row_indices1, ]


Creating Binary Debt Classification

# Calculate median debt
median_debt = median(data1$DEBT, na.rm = TRUE)

# Create binary debt classification
data1$DEBT_CLASS = ifelse(data1$DEBT > median_debt, "High", "Low")
data1$DEBT_CLASS = factor(data1$DEBT_CLASS, levels = c("Low", "High"))

# Create summary of debt classification
debt_summary = table(data1$DEBT_CLASS)

The correlation analysis identifies key relationships between financial and demographic variables: • Income and Assets (Strongest Correlation): A strong positive correlation exists between income and assets, indicating that individuals with higher income levels tend to accumulate more assets.
• Financial Literacy and Education: A positive correlation suggests that individuals with higher education levels generally have better financial literacy.
• Debt and Assets: A positive correlation between debt and assets implies that individuals with more assets also tend to carry higher debt, possibly due to mortgages or investment-related borrowing.
• Debt and Income: A positive correlation indicates that higher-income individuals tend to have higher debt levels, potentially due to greater access to credit and investment opportunities.

2. Normality Check



Shapiro-Wilk Test

LDA & QDA assume normality.   Shapiro-Wilk test for univariate normality check.

# Apply Shapiro-Wilk test to all numeric predictors
numeric_vars = c("DEBT", "INCOME", "ASSET", "CCBAL", "AGE", "EDUC", "FINLIT")

#### INCOME, ASSET, CCBAL, AGE, EDUC, FINLIT, MARRIED, HHSEX, LATE, FORECLLAST5, BNKRUPLAST5

normality_results = sapply(data1[numeric_vars], function(x) shapiro.test(x)$p.value)

# Print results
print("Shapiro-Wilk Test for Normality:")
## [1] "Shapiro-Wilk Test for Normality:"
print(normality_results)
##         DEBT       INCOME        ASSET        CCBAL          AGE         EDUC 
## 1.608043e-91 2.785240e-91 2.414443e-89 7.257933e-84 4.921709e-21 5.554486e-48 
##       FINLIT 
## 1.626484e-62

From the above we see that the p-values are less than and alpha of 0.05, thus we reject the null hypothesis and conclude that there is no statistical evidence that the individual variables are normally distributed.

3. Check for Equal Variance

(Box’s M Test for LDA)


LDA assumes that different groups have the same variance-covariance structure.

# Run Box's M Test
box_m_test = boxM(data1[numeric_vars], data1$DEBT_CLASS)
print("Box's M Test Results:")
## [1] "Box's M Test Results:"
print(box_m_test)
## 
##  Box's M-test for Homogeneity of Covariance Matrices
## 
## data:  data1[numeric_vars]
## Chi-Sq (approx.) = 31172, df = 28, p-value < 2.2e-16

With a p-value of 2.2e-16 at an alpha of 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis (that there is equal covariance in each class with respect to the features). Thus, the dataset failed the equal covariance check.


4. Multicollinearity Check


Variance Inflation Factor - VIF*

LDA & QDA require that predictors are not highly correlated.

# Fit a linear model to compute VIF
vif_model <- lm(DEBT ~ ., data = data1[numeric_vars])
alias(vif_model)
## Model :
## DEBT ~ INCOME + ASSET + CCBAL + AGE + EDUC + FINLIT
vif_values <- vif(vif_model)

print("Variance Inflation Factor (VIF) for Predictors:")
## [1] "Variance Inflation Factor (VIF) for Predictors:"
print(vif_values)
##   INCOME    ASSET    CCBAL      AGE     EDUC   FINLIT 
## 1.991648 2.044814 1.003613 1.039754 1.147861 1.144850

From the above, the VIF for all the respective variables is less than 5 which implies that multicollinearity is not an issue for the application of LDA and QDA to this dataset. Note that if the VIFs were > 10 for any variable, then multicollinearity would have been an issue with respect to that variable.


Model Build


Data Preparation


# Create dataset for modeling
model_data = data1 %>%
  dplyr::select(DEBT_CLASS, INCOME, ASSET, CCBAL, AGE, EDUC, FINLIT, MARRIED, HHSEX, LATE, FORECLLAST5, BNKRUPLAST5) %>%
  na.omit()

# Train-test split
set.seed(123)
train_index = createDataPartition(model_data$DEBT_CLASS, p = 0.7, list = FALSE)
train_data = model_data[train_index, ]
test_data = model_data[-train_index, ]

1. Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA)


# Train LDA model
lda_model = lda(DEBT_CLASS ~ ., data = train_data)

# Make predictions on test set
lda_pred = predict(lda_model, test_data)
lda_class = lda_pred$class

# Calculate accuracy
lda_conf_matrix = table(Predicted = lda_class, Actual = test_data$DEBT_CLASS)
lda_accuracy = sum(diag(lda_conf_matrix))/sum(lda_conf_matrix)

# Print results
print("LDA Model Performance:")
## [1] "LDA Model Performance:"
print(lda_conf_matrix)
##          Actual
## Predicted Low High
##      Low  447  218
##      High 243  469
print(paste("LDA Accuracy:", round(lda_accuracy, 3)))
## [1] "LDA Accuracy: 0.665"
# Plot LDA discriminant scores
lda_data = data.frame(
  score = lda_pred$x,
  class = test_data$DEBT_CLASS
)

ggplot(lda_data, aes(x = LD1, fill = class)) +
  geom_density(alpha = 0.5) +
  labs(title = "LDA Discriminant Scores",
       x = "First Linear Discriminant",
       y = "Density") +
  theme_minimal()

# Calculate and plot ROC curve for LDA
lda_roc = roc(test_data$DEBT_CLASS, lda_pred$posterior[,2])
plot(lda_roc, main = "ROC Curve for LDA",
     col = "blue", lwd = 2)
text(0.6, 0.2, paste("AUC =", round(auc(lda_roc), 3)))

3. Random Forest


# Load necessary libraries
library(randomForest)
library(pROC)  # For AUC calculation

# Train Random Forest model
rf_model = randomForest(DEBT_CLASS ~ ., 
                        data = train_data,
                        ntree = 500,
                        importance = TRUE)

# Variable importance plot
varImpPlot(rf_model,
           main = "Variable Importance Plot",
           sort = TRUE)

# Make predictions on test set
rf_pred = predict(rf_model, test_data)

# Calculate accuracy
conf_matrix = table(Predicted = rf_pred, Actual = test_data$DEBT_CLASS)
accuracy_rf = sum(diag(conf_matrix)) / sum(conf_matrix)

# Print Accuracy Results
print("Random Forest Model Performance:")
## [1] "Random Forest Model Performance:"
print(conf_matrix)
##          Actual
## Predicted Low High
##      Low  526  179
##      High 164  508
print(paste("Accuracy:", round(accuracy_rf, 3)))
## [1] "Accuracy: 0.751"
# -------------------------------------------
# **AUC Calculation**
# -------------------------------------------

# Get class probabilities
rf_prob = predict(rf_model, test_data, type = "prob")

# Ensure DEBT_CLASS is a factor
test_data$DEBT_CLASS = as.factor(test_data$DEBT_CLASS)  

# Compute AUC using pROC
roc_curve = roc(test_data$DEBT_CLASS, rf_prob[,2])  # Assuming second column is the positive class probability

# Print AUC value
auc_value = auc(roc_curve)
print(paste("AUC:", round(auc_value, 3)))
## [1] "AUC: 0.836"
# -------------------------------------------
# **Plot ROC Curve with AUC Displayed**
# -------------------------------------------
plot(roc_curve, col = "blue", lwd = 2, main = "ROC Curve for Random Forest")
abline(a = 0, b = 1, lty = 2, col = "gray")  # Diagonal reference line

# Add AUC value as text on the plot
text(0.6, 0.2, paste("AUC =", round(auc_value, 3)), col = "red", cex = 1.2, font = 2)
